<break time="1s" />
OpenAI winds down Sora, bets on Spud

<break time="1s" />
OpenAI shut down its Sora AI video generator this week, freeing up compute for the company's next major model, internally called Spud. Sam Altman told staff the company would wind down all video products, including the mobile app and the API, with employees describing Sora as a drag on resources. Altman said the released compute would go toward Spud, which he indicated could be ready within weeks. The Sora team's lead said the group would pivot toward world simulation for robotics, framing the new goal as automating the physical economy. The shutdown illustrated the economic realities of compute-heavy media generation, where inference costs per generated minute had become unsustainable.

<break time="1s" />

The move also carries business implications. A partnership and one billion dollar investment from Disney, which had agreed to have its intellectual property used in Sora, was placed on hold following the announcement. Organizational changes accompanied the product decision as well, with Altman reportedly shifting safety responsibilities under a different executive and renaming the consumer deployment division to AGI Deployment.

