Directions in AI Architecture

<break time="1s" />
MCP crosses 97 million installs

<break time="1s" />
On March 25, 2026, Anthropic's Model Context Protocol crossed 97 million installs, a figure representing the fastest adoption curve for any AI infrastructure standard in history. Every major AI provider now ships MCP-compatible tooling as a default, with OpenAI, Google DeepMind, Cohere, and Mistral all integrating MCP support into their agent frameworks within a ninety day window. The protocol, originally released in November 2024, provides a standard way for AI agents to connect to external tools, databases, and services without custom connector development for each integration.

<break time="1s" />

The practical consequences are visible in enterprise deployments. When Block deployed MCP across their financial data infrastructure, they eliminated 340 custom connectors. Apollo integrated MCP into their go-to-market platform and cut integration maintenance overhead by sixty percent. The MCP server ecosystem has grown to more than 5,800 community and enterprise servers covering databases, CRMs, cloud providers, productivity tools, developer tools, and analytics services. For practitioners building agentic workflows, that means the integration work for most common business applications is already done.

<break time="1s" />
Hyperagents rewrite their own improvement loops

<break time="1s" />
Researchers from the University of British Columbia, Vector Institute, New York University, the University of Edinburgh, and Meta published results this week on what they call hyperagents, a framework in which a language model can improve not only its task performance but the mechanism it uses to generate future improvements. The approach, formally called Darwin Godel Machine Hyperagents, integrates a task agent that solves a target problem and a meta agent that modifies both the task agent and itself, enabling metacognitive self-modification.

<break time="1s" />

The research tested the approach across four domains. On a paper review prediction task, the hyperagent improved performance from zero at baseline to 0.71 on a binary accept-reject benchmark. On a robotics reward design task, performance rose from 0.06 to 0.37, surpassing the default reward function used as a target. Most runs used Claude Sonnet 4.5 as the base model. The authors acknowledged that an AI system capable of autonomously improving itself on arbitrary domains carries a range of safety issues, some of which they described as potentially serious, and called for ongoing human verification.

<break time="1s" />
HorizonMath sets a benchmark for unsolved problems

<break time="1s" />
Researchers at Oxford, Harvard, Princeton, and the Ellison Institute of Technology released HorizonMath, a new benchmark containing one hundred problems across eight domains in applied and computational mathematics, most of them currently unsolved. Because the solutions are unknown, they do not exist in any training corpus, meaning a correct solution produced by a model would signal genuine reasoning ability rather than pattern matching.

<break time="1s" />

On the full dataset, the highest scoring model was GPT 5.4 Pro at seven percent, followed by Claude Opus 4.6 and Gemini 3.1 Pro, which both scored three percent. On the easiest subset of problems, where known closed form solutions exist, GPT 5.4 Pro led at fifty percent, with Opus 4.6 and Gemini 3.1 both reaching thirty percent. The benchmark is designed to resist contamination over time, since any correct answer to an unsolved problem would itself be a novel mathematical result.

