Google researchers propose a society of AI minds

<break time="1s" />
Researchers at Google published a paper this week arguing that the most consequential form of future intelligence will not be a single dominant AI system but an ecosystem of AI agents working alongside humans through institutions and social structures. The paper draws a line from primate social groups through human language and writing through law and bureaucracy, arguing that each prior intelligence explosion emerged not from upgrades to individual cognitive hardware but from new, socially aggregated units of cognition.

<break time="1s" />

The researchers write that the path to more powerful AI runs not through building a single colossal oracle but through composing richer social systems, and that these systems will be hybrid, mixing human and AI participants. The paper argues that governing this future will require new institutions, including AI systems with explicitly invested public values whose function is to check and balance AI deployed by the private sector. The authors compare these future institutional needs to courts, markets, and bureaucracies, arguing that scalable AI ecosystems will require digital equivalents.

