Stanford researcher maps a path to political AI tools

<break time="1s" />
A Stanford political economy professor published a widely read essay this week arguing that AI could give every person access to what he calls political superintelligence, but that reaching that outcome requires intentional design at every layer of how these systems are built and governed. By political superintelligence, the author means AI tools that help citizens, representatives, and institutions perceive reality more sharply, understand trade-offs, contest power, and act more effectively.

<break time="1s" />

The essay identifies three layers that would need to be developed together. The first is an information layer, where AI changes how governments access and understand data. The second is a representation layer, where AI delegates monitor politics on behalf of individual citizens. The third is a governance layer, which addresses the fact that even if political superintelligence arrives, the infrastructure that powers it would be owned and operated by a small number of private companies. The author argues that getting this right requires AI developers to invest more in transparency tools, and that policymakers and the public need to demand more of AI companies in building these capabilities responsibly.

